Array
-----
1. Array is a non-primitive datatype(reference type).
2. Array is a collection of Homogenous(same type) elements.
3. Arrays are dynamic allocated in java.
4. Array works on the concept of indexing.
5. Array indexing always starts from zero because it follows number system.
6. Prerequisite for array allocation is base address.
7. Array works on continous memory allocation.
8. Arrays are object in java.
9. Array can hold primitive as well as object reference.
10. Type of Array : 
    a. One Dimensional Array 
    b. Two Dimensional Array
        |-- There is a special type of two dimensional array i.e Jagged Array, which can have different columns for each row. 
    c. Multidimensional array

11. Array elements shares same name but differentiable by there indexing. 

12. Syntax : 
    i. <datatype> <array name>[] = {element1, element2, ...., element_n}; 
    ex : int arr[] = {1,2,3,4,5};

    int a;
    int a,b;
    int a,b,c,d,e;
    int a1,a2,a3,...a50;
    
    int arr[50];

    arr[0] arr[1] arr[2] .... arr[49]